<div id="pf9f" class="pf w0 h0" data-page-no="9f"><div class="pc pc9f w0 h0"><img class="bi x0 y0 w1 h1" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/><div class="t m0 x30 h13 y86 ffa fse fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">1<span class="_ _11"> </span><span class="fsf">Andre<span class="_ _8"></span>w S. Gro<span class="_ _b"></span>ve<span class="_ _8"></span>, </span></div><div class="t m2 x94 h14 y86 ff4 fsf fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">High Output Management</div><div class="t m0 x95 h13 y86 ffa fsf fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0"> (New Y<span class="_ _a"></span>ork: Vintage Books<span class="_ _b"></span>, 1983).</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y28 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws571">space. I’ve also seen managers from startups who were used to being able to act</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y29 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbe5">on whatever they thought was most important struggle in environments that</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y2a ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws485">required more <span class="ff7 ws0">sign-o</span> from other parties. This is the most obvious cultural ele-</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y2b ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws8f4">ment. If you value servant-leadership and you hire a manager who wants to dic-</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y2c ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws9b5">tate exact marching orders to the team, there will be a bad <span class="ff7 ws0">t.</span> Similarly, if you</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y87 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbe6">value collaboration and hire a manager who thinks that the loudest voice in any</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y88 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">conversation should win, you will also have problems.</div><div class="t m0 x16 h8 y89 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws67e">Culture <span class="ff7 ws0">t</span> is so important in managers because they shape their teams to</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y8b ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbe7">their culture, and they hire new people based on their cultural ideas. If you hire a</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y8c ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsa69">manager who doesn’t <span class="ff7 ws0">t</span> in culturally with the team she’s managing, one of two</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y8d ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbe8">things is likely to happen: the manager will fail and you’ll have to <span class="ff7 ws0">re</span><span class="wsbe9"> her, or</span></div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y8e ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbea">most of the team will quit and then you may still have to <span class="ff7 ws0">re</span> her. Sometimes</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y8f ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbeb">changing the culture of an area is inevitable, and hiring in a new manager will</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y90 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbec">hasten that change. You can use management changes to your advantage in this</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y91 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws77f">way. In fact, you see this frequently at growing startups, where they hire in more</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y92 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbed">seasoned managers and executives to round out the lack of experience of the rest</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y93 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws21">of the team. Sometimes this works incredibly well, and sometimes it’s a massive</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y94 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsb74">failure. No matter what, you will usually see attrition happening around the hire</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y106 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">of these bearers of new and <span class="ff7">dierent</span> culture, so proceed here with caution.</div><div class="t m0 x16 h8 y107 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbee">In his book <span class="ff5">High Output Management</span><span class="ws0">,</span></div><div class="t m0 x96 h15 y7cb ff6 fs10 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">1</div><div class="t m0 x97 h8 y107 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbef"> Andy Grove talks about cultural val-</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y108 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf0">ues as one of the ways that people make decisions inside of highly complex,</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y109 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf1">uncertain, or ambiguous circumstances where they value the group interest</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y10a ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf2">above their own. I <span class="ff7 ws0">nd</span> this insight very powerful. His observation is that most</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y10b ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws7b4">new hires act in self-interest until they get to know their colleagues, and then</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y10c ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws792">they move into group interest. So, if you start them in a highly complex or uncer-</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y10d ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf3">tain job, they tend to fail unless they quickly settle into the cultural norms and</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y10e ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf4">use cultural values to align their decision making. If you can screen for managers</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y10f ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf5">who naturally gravitate toward the cultural values that your company already pos-</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y110 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf6">sesses, they are more likely to make this shift quickly than managers who have</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y112 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">very <span class="ff7">dierent</span> personal beliefs.</div><div class="t m0 x16 h8 y113 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 ws882">F<span class="_ _8"></span>inally, I would be remiss if I did not point out one of the critical elements to</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y114 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf7">hiring in new managers: the reference check. Do thorough reference checks for</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y115 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf8">anyone you’re planning to bring on board, even if you’ve worked with that person</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y116 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbf9">before. Ask the references to describe the ways that the person succeeds as well</div><div class="t m0 x23 h8 y117 ff6 fs3 fc2 sc0 ls0 wsbfa">as the ways she fails. Ask them if they would work with or for this person again.</div><div class="t m0 x8f h12 ya4 ff9 fsd fc2 sc0 ls0 ws0">MANA<span class="_ _b"></span>GING MANA<span class="_ _b"></span>GERS <span class="_ _12"> </span>| <span class="_ _c"> </span>1<span class="_ _b"></span>43</div><a class="l" href="#pf9f" data-dest-detail='[159,"XYZ",null,70,null]'><div class="d m1" style="border-style:none;position:absolute;left:525.673403px;bottom:711.278565px;width:2.322010px;height:6.000000px;background-color:rgba(255,255,255,0.000001);"></div></a></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[2.314815,0.000000,0.000000,2.314815,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
